1087","1085":"1085","1062":"1062","1128":"1128","1139":"1139","1104":"1104","1069":"1069","1135":"1135","1157":"1157","1112":"1112","1134":"1134","Roye, Somme, Picardie, França":"Roye, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Moreuil, Somme, Picardie, França":"Moreuil, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Roye, Somme, Picardie, France":"Roye, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Moreuil, Somme, Picardie, France":"Moreuil, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1085–1134":"1085–1134","1087–1139":"1087–1139","1062–1104":"1062–1104","1104–1157":"1104–1157","1135–1197":"1135–1197","1054–1112":"1054–1112","1069–1128":"1069–1128","1054":"1054","1197":"1197","1087":"1087","1085":"1085","1062":"1062","1128":"1128","1139":"1139","1104":"1104","1069":"1069","1135":"1135","1157":"1157","1112":"1112","1134":"1134","Roye, Somme, Picardie, França":"Roye, Somme, Picardie, France","Moreuil, Somme, Picardie, França":"Moreuil, Somme, Picardie, France","Roye, Somme, Picardie, France":"Roye, Somme, Picardie, France","Moreuil, Somme, Picardie, France":"Moreuil, Somme, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Adèle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]},{"name":"Agnès","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adèle Agnès De Moreuil was born in 1085, in Moreuil, Somme, Picardie, France, her father, Gaucher De Moreuil, was 31 and her mother, Marie De Vermandois, was 16. She had at least 2 sons with Evrard Girard De Roye. She died in 1134, in Roye, Somme, Picardie, France, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1085–1134":"1085–1134","1087–1139":"1087–1139","1062–1104":"1062–1104","1104–1157":"1104–1157","1135–1197":"1135–1197","1054–1112":"1054–1112","1069–1128":"1069–1128","1054":"1054","1197":"1197","1087":"1087","1085":"1085","1062":"1062","1128":"1128","1139":"1139","1104":"1104","1069":"1069","1135":"1135","1157":"1157","1112":"1112","1134":"1134","Roye, Somme, Picardie, França":"Roye, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Moreuil, Somme, Picardie, França":"Moreuil, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Roye, Somme, Picardie, France":"Roye, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Moreuil, Somme, Picardie, France":"Moreuil, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1085–1134":"1085–1134","1087–1139":"1087–1139","1062–1104":"1062–1104","1104–1157":"1104–1157","113